			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Greetings one and all! This is my first post to the site so please bear with me.  :oops: But I must relate an experience I've had, and will hopefully continue this evening, that I think the rest of you may both enjoy and make use of.
<br />

<br />
 I have recently created Zairyn, a gnomish mage who just dinged lvl 10. I was bored with hunting orcs in gfay and CB as it is all the same. You have some green-skinned ape-like thing bearing down on you. So I traveled to Kaladim in the Butcherblock Mtns. on business with a Mr. Canloe Nusback. He informed me at the close of our deal that there was an encampment of relatively large monstrosities near to the Dagnor's Cauldron area. He asked if there was anything I could do to look into the situation and possibly rectify it.
<br />
 I mentioned to Mr. Nusback that I was seriously doubtful of my qualifications for such a task but he assured me that I would glean much by just "looking in on it".
<br />
 Upon leaving glorious Kaladim I chose not to investigate these behemoths in prefrence to collecting a few bones at a place my father's father talked quite often about. He called it the Chessboard. Well, as the fates would have it, upon my arrival at the Chessboard with a childhood friend of mine, a fellow gnome and wizard two circles my senior, we discovered one of those stuffy High Elven Paladins reclining against a tree and munching away at an apple. A large pile of bones, quite taller than myself, lay not too far off from him.
<br />
 When we approched this snobbish individual and asked if he meant to wipe out the entire encampment of the Haunted Chessboard we were greeted only with arrogant silence. Having a mind to sic Xabner, my current Son of Fire who was adequately armored and armed, on him I stood my ground and fumed. My ears turning white hot, mose nose glowing three shade of crimson.
<br />
 Just as I was about to say something my friend said that she felt he wasn't going to respond and that we should leave the encampment to him. Maybe the skeleons will have a bone to pick with him for exterminating their ilk? A thought which gave me great pleasure to envision.
<br />

<br />
 Now, not knowing where to go or what to do we flustered about near the road running between the Greater Faydark and Kaladim. A nice merchant there bought our loot of goblin heads, viles of blood, and a nice little gold token my companion took from what she called "a giant brute" upon his demise.
<br />
 That remark of "Giant Brute" reminded me of Mr. Nusback's proposition to me regarding the "Large Monstrosities" near Dagnor's.  So I made the same proposal to my friend that Mr. Nusback made to me and we decided to go and see whats what.
<br />
 Now, it was dawn by the time we reached our destination. What we found frightened us as much as excited us. At the base of a very tall tower there, standing on guard, were three quite large beings whose beauty is equaled only to the jam between my wee toes! Fully armored and armed they glared about lokoing out for danger. What was in the tower we knew not.
<br />
 So, deciding against better judgement I decided to lure one of the ogres into the bushes where we sat. I beckoned for Gaboner to join me in this goal and right quickly a bulge appeared in the ground at my feet. First an arm, then a hand followed by another arm and yet another hand. Before long, with sod and underbrush falling off, stood my earthen companion. I gave him the onyl weapon I had on me, a staff of tracing that my father had taught me to summon.
<br />
 I warned my friend that if she did not feel comfortable with my decision she could head back to the road and await my arrival. I looked to her for confirmation of my words and found her quietly running down the hill towards the road.
<br />
 "Well my friend, it is just you and I" I commented to Gaboner, more for my assurance than his/hers.
<br />

<br />
 Focusing on the beastly creature in armor I whispered ancient words of power and before long the brute and he alone came rushing at my direction. The closer he got the worser he smelt and I was so distracted by his awesome flabby form I forgot to give directions to Gaboner. Thankfully, however, I snapped to and told my friend to Attack.
<br />
 Rushing in headlong Gaboner entered the fight by causing the behemoth's feet to sink into the ground, then he proceded to wail on him with my staff of tracing. I of course stood back and burned the daylights out of the ogre, healed Gaboner when I felt safe to do so, and bathed him in flames for better offensive ability.
<br />

<br />
 The sun rose to its fullest and a light fog spread across the mountainous landscape and all was quiet. I looked about me and realized that I was not dead, nor did I lose Gaboner! I felt a rush of excitement as I knew that this battle gave me more knowledge and experience that those pathetic orcs in Crushbone. Gaboner, while alive, was pretty badly hurt so I released him to his native plane and decided to return to Kaladim myself for some much needed rest. The excitement of the event kept me going all the way back to the Dwarven capitol.
<br />

<br />
 Tonight, when the shadows cover the ground and the wolves sing their meloncholy song I will venture out once more to meet the ogres near Dagnor's. This time better prepared. I will call for Xonn's aid tonight as his firery personality will make things, hopefully, go much smoother. I bought plenty of armor to equip him with, only leather but it will have to do. And we will see just how mighty these creatures are. I will let you all know how I fared. :wink: 
<br />

<br />
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<br />

<br />
Layman's terms; Facing Dagnor's Cauldron zone entrance turn left. Look for the tower with the ogres about it. At lvl 10 they con yellow and red to me. I took down a yellow one last night with an unarmored earth elemental. Tonight I plan on revisiting them and trying a red, this time having a fire elemental equipped with armor. Maybe this will compensate for his lower-than-earth's HP but also allow him his full dmg capability. We'll see. For those of you twinked out there, it might be better experience than crushbone, which is full 90% of the time in my exp. Or the chessboard which seems to be always camped when I go there. These ogres I have seen camped only once when I was my druid. Might be worth a shot!
<br />

<br />
Good Luck!<br />_________________<br />Zairyn the Wise
<br />

<br />
"Do not be so quick to deal out death...not even the wise can see all ends".
<br />
 -Gandalf; LOTR</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
